ktool.dyld module¶

class ktool.dyld.BindingTable(library)¶

Bases: object

The binding table contains a ton of information related to the binding info in the library

.lookup_table Contains a map of address -> Symbol declarations which should be used for processing off-image

symbol decorations

.symbol_table Contains a full list of symbols declared in the binding info. Avoid iterating through this for speed

purposes.

Unprocessed:

.actions contains a list of, you guessed it, actions.

.import_stack contains a fairly raw unprocessed list of binding info commands

class ktool.dyld.Dyld¶

Bases: object

This is a static class containing several methods for, essentially, recreating the functionality of Dyld for our own purposes.

It isnt meant to be a faithful recreation of dyld so to speak, it just does things dyld also does, kinda.

static load(macho_slice)¶

Take a slice of a macho file and process it using the dyld functions

Parameters

macho_slice – Slice to load. If your library is not fat, that’ll be MachOFile.slices[0]

Returns

Processed Library object

class ktool.dyld.Library(macho_slice)¶

Bases: object

This class represents the Mach-O Binary as a whole.

It’s the root object in the massive tree of information we’re going to build up about the binary

This is an abstracted version, other classes will handle the raw struct interaction;

here, we facilitate that interaction within those classes and generate our abstract representation

Calling __init__ on this class will kickstart the full process.

(end location, value)

get_bytes(offset: int, length: int, vm=False, section_name=None)¶

Get a sequence of bytes (as an int) from a location

Parameters

  • offset – Offset within the library

  • length – Amount of bytes to get

  • vm – Is offset a VM address

  • section_name – Section Name if vm==True (improves translation time slightly)

Returns

length Bytes at offset

get_cstr_at(address: int, limit: int = 0, vm=False, section_name=None)¶

Load a C style string from a location, stopping once a null byte is encountered.

Parameters

  • address – Address to load string from

  • limit – Limit of the length of bytes, 0 = unlimited

  • vm – Is address a VM address?

  • section_name – if vm==True, the section name (vastly improves VM lookup time)

Returns

The loaded C string

get_str_at(address: int, count: int, vm=False, section_name=None)¶

Get string with set length from location (to be used essentially only for loading segment names)

Parameters

  • address – Address of string start

  • count – Length of string

  • vm – Is address a VM address?

  • section_name – if vm==True, the section name (unused here, really)

Returns

The loaded string.

load_struct(address: int, struct_type: ktool.structs.struct, vm=False, section_name=None, endian='little')¶

Load a struct (struct_type_t) from a location and return the processed object

Parameters

  • address – Address to load struct from

  • struct_type – type of struct (e.g. dyld_header_t)

  • vm – Is address a VM address?

  • section_name – if vm==True, the section name (slightly improves translation speed)

  • endian – Endianness of bytes to read.

Returns

Loaded struct

class ktool.dyld.LibraryHeader(macho_slice)¶

Bases: object

This class represents the Mach-O Header It contains the basic header info along with all load commands within it.

It doesn’t handle complex abstraction logic, it simply loads in the load commands as their raw structs

class ktool.dyld.Symbol(lib, cmd=None, entry=None, fullname=None, ordinal=None, addr=None)¶

Bases: object

This class can represent several types of symbols.

It can represent an external or internal symbol declaration and is used for both across the library

.external is a BOOL that can be used to check whether it’s an external or internal declaration

.fullname contains the full name of the symbol (e.g. _OBJC_CLASS_$_MyDumbClassnameHere)

.name contains the (somewhat) processed name of the symbol (e.g. _MyDumbClassnameHere for an @interface MyDumbClassnameHere)

.type contains a SymbolType if it was able to figure one out

.addr contains the address of the symbol in the image
